h3. Summary
 * 'Table of Contents' macro gets misaligned, on the new editor, if inserted into 'Columns' macro, losing its left alignment and becoming squished on the center of the page, it this macro is placed specifically within the first column on the left.

h3. Environment
 * New Confluence editor;
 * 'Table of Contents' macro is supposed to be left aligned when inserted into a page, independently where it is placed;
 * Inserting the 'Table of Contents' macro into the left column of a 'Columns' macro (either a 2 or 3 sections column) will break the alignment of the 'Table of Contents' macro, bringing the table of contents to the center of the page, and squishing all of its content, as can be seen in the next screenshot.
 * This behavior is present if the "Centre" option is selected on the 'Columns' macro. (selecting "Wide" or "Full Width" options do not generate this behavior);
 !Screen Shot 2019-02-25 at 15.36.19.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page using the new editor;
 # Add some text headings;
 # Insert a 'Columns' macro on the page;
 # Insert 'Table of Contents' macro into the left column (of the 'Columns' macro) - This can either be a 2 or 3 section column layout, the result will be the same;
 (This behavior is also present if the 'Table of Contents' is within the 'Table of Contents Zone' when inserted into the 'Columns' macro);
 !Screen Shot 2019-02-25 at 15.36.42.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Expected Results
 * 'Table of Contents' to be left aligned within the column;
 !Screen Shot 2019-02-25 at 15.37.17.png|thumbnail!

h3. Actual Results
 * 'Table of Contents' is brought to the center of the page, losing its left alignment, and its content is squished. (if the "centre" option is selected on the 'Columns' macro)
 !Screen Shot 2019-02-25 at 15.36.19.png|thumbnail!

h3. Workaround
 * Select "Wide" or "Full Width" options when using the 'Columns' macro in this case.

 !Screen Shot 2019-02-25 at 15.39.06.png|thumbnail! 
 !Screen Shot 2019-02-25 at 15.39.10.png|thumbnail!

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-30756].
  {panel}

*Request Background*

Currently Confluence HTML export shipped out Confluence style sheet with it and it generate great HTML pages for users to use. However it still doesn't provide a header and footer that looks like Confluence layout.

It would be great if we could provide an HTML export that looks a lot more similar to Confluence page.

h3. Problem Definition
The new macro called *Panel* in the new editor allows users to contextually switch between:
* Info - {color:blue}Blue{color}
* Note - {color:purple}Purple{color}
* Success - {color:green}Green{color}
* Warning - {color:orange}Orange{color}
* Error - {color:red}Red{color}

 !Screenshot 2019-08-22 at 11.50.14.png|thumbnail! 

There's no option for the user to choose on their own which of the icons or colors show, or if they want an icon to show at all.

h3. Suggested Solution
Customers should be able to edit/change/set the background color for panel macro and choose if they want to display an icon.

h3. Why this is important
The customer wants to customize the panel macro, which they are not able to do because of the new editor changes.

h3. Workaround 
No current workaround, but I've used the new Layout feature mentioned in [Confluence Editing Improvements|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confcloud/confluence-editing-improvements-945107733.html] to display as a panel of my own.

Allow further customization of the "Road Planner Macro" used on Confluence's editor. Some ideas would be:

* Be able to change the colors of the bars individually and independently from the header's color;

* Be able to add different color markers;

* Be able to see dates and markers when scrolling the page;

* Add additional formatting options;
